## Code Review – PR 6501814 (`users/timpham/service-tree-permissions-fix`)

### ✅ No issues: Deleted interfaces/classes with no remaining callers

- `IServiceTreeClient`, `ServiceTreeClient`, `GetNodesByIdsAsync`, `GetNodesByInternalIdsAsync`, `GetServiceHierarchyAsync` — **zero references found** anywhere in the repo. These deletions are clean.
- Removed `ServiceTreeNode` properties (`InternalId`, `ParentInternalId`, `ParentId`, `OrganizationPath`, `NodeType`, `ParentNodeType`) — **no callers found** outside the deleted files.
- Removed `ServiceTreeKustoOptions` properties (`TableName`, `OrganizationFunctionName`, `UseOrganizationFunction`, `IdColumnName`) — **no callers found** (the `TableName` hits in grep results are entirely unrelated classes).
- `TryLoadAadCertificate` rename — **no external callers found**; it's only called from within `ServiceTreeKustoClient` itself, and the call site was updated correctly. The removal of the post-call null check is safe because the method now always throws on failure rather than returning null.
- Constructor `this.tokenCredential.GetType().Name` — **not a null-deref risk**. The logging line at line 91 only runs after the explicit null check at lines 76–81 (`if (this.tokenCredential == null) { ... return; }`). `tokenCredential` is guaranteed non-null at that point.

---

### 🐛 BUG 1 — Exception rethrowing in `QueryHierarchyBatchAsync` now causes all concurrent batches to be silently abandoned (behavioral regression for large inputs)

**File:** `ServiceTreeKustoClient.cs`, lines 119–136 (`GetHierarchyNodesByServiceIdsAsync`)

**What changed:** `QueryHierarchyBatchAsync` previously swallowed non-cancellation exceptions (logged as Warning, returned empty). It now logs as Error and **rethrows**.

**The bug:** The calling code uses `Task.WhenAll` over a fan-out of concurrent batch tasks:

```csharp
var tasks = batches.Select(async batch =>
{
    await semaphore.WaitAsync(cancellationToken);
    try
    {
        var batchResults = await this.QueryHierarchyBatchAsync(batch, cancellationToken);
        foreach (var pair in batchResults) { results[pair.Key] = pair.Value; }
    }
    finally
    {
        semaphore.Release();
    }
}).ToList();

await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
```

The `try/finally` block around the batch query has **no `catch`**. When `QueryHierarchyBatchAsync` rethrows, the exception propagates out of that lambda and faults the task. `Task.WhenAll` then throws on the first faulted task — but crucially, **any in-flight or pending batches are not awaited after that point**. The `ConcurrentDictionary results` will be **partially populated** (whichever batches completed before the failure), and the exception propagates all the way up to callers.

Before this PR, a single Kusto transient error on one batch would degrade gracefully — that batch returned empty, the rest of the results were still usable. After this PR, a single transient Kusto error on **any one batch** throws an exception that reaches:

- `ServiceTreeParentResolver.ResolveParentsAsync` (no try/catch around the `GetHierarchyNodesByServiceIdsAsync` call — the exception propagates out),
- then up to `PapyrusConfigController.GetServiceAuthQuotaParentInfoAsync` (no try/catch — the controller will return HTTP 500),
- and `AppIdToProductResolver.ResolveAsync` (has a top-level catch, so it silently returns an empty result — but silently breaking a whole feature is arguably worse than degraded results).

The previous swallow-and-warn behavior was intentional partial-fault tolerance. The new rethrow is arguably the right *logging* choice, but **the fan-out caller was not updated to handle failures per-batch**, making this a behavioral regression under any transient Kusto error.

---

### ✅ No other real bugs found

All other changes (dead code removal, `LoadAadCertificate` throw-instead-of-null, constructor logging) are correct given the post-PR code.

